[SPEAKER_08]: I'm concerned that it goes back and forth and mayor, you know, appoint someone in the city council.

586
00:48:26,791 --> 00:48:28,733
[SPEAKER_08]: Now, because it's mayor, we don't like the mayor.

587
00:48:28,753 --> 00:48:29,733
[SPEAKER_08]: We're not going to go along.

588
00:48:30,594 --> 00:48:31,155
[SPEAKER_08]: We've seen that.

589
00:48:31,175 --> 00:48:32,916
[SPEAKER_08]: Well, isn't that the case now?

590
00:48:33,697 --> 00:48:35,139
[SPEAKER_08]: It certainly is Anthony.

591
00:48:35,159 --> 00:48:36,460
[SPEAKER_08]: We've seen it for a hundred years.

592
00:48:36,500 --> 00:48:37,080
[SPEAKER_08]: You know that.

593
00:48:37,661 --> 00:48:37,961
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah.

594
00:48:38,221 --> 00:48:45,108
[SPEAKER_06]: But isn't there like, uh, isn't they do have some commissions and some committees that they,

595
00:48:46,219 --> 00:48:48,842
[SPEAKER_06]: people do have to go before the City Council.

596
00:48:49,242 --> 00:48:50,544
[SPEAKER_10]: Am I correct?

597
00:48:51,325 --> 00:48:56,310
[SPEAKER_10]: I think there's one or two and I believe that there are ordinances about those.

598
00:48:57,391 --> 00:48:59,013
[SPEAKER_10]: I think the Liquor Commission is one of them.

599
00:49:01,015 --> 00:49:04,339
[SPEAKER_06]: And isn't the Election Commission one of them as well?

600
00:49:04,359 --> 00:49:05,520
[SPEAKER_06]: Yes.

601
00:49:07,048 --> 00:49:16,734
[SPEAKER_08]: And just recently, I think the whole committee, you know, the council has a vote and the mayor has a vote, and then there's a recommendation for someone else.

602
00:49:16,794 --> 00:49:21,257
[SPEAKER_08]: And so there's a few of them that are like that.

603
00:49:21,817 --> 00:49:25,059
[SPEAKER_10]: So and that can be done by ordinance.

604
00:49:26,020 --> 00:49:32,343
[SPEAKER_10]: Because obviously, because our current charter says that the mayor makes all appointments without city council confirmation, so.

605
00:49:35,785 --> 00:49:36,546
[SPEAKER_10]: OK, Aubrey.

606
00:49:37,007 --> 00:49:37,768
[SPEAKER_10]: you've had your hand up.

607
00:49:39,889 --> 00:49:41,371
[SPEAKER_09]: I have a different question.

608
00:49:41,451 --> 00:49:45,554
[SPEAKER_09]: So it's about the removals and suspensions piece.

609
00:49:45,574 --> 00:49:52,040
[SPEAKER_09]: So right now, the way it works is that the mayor can remove or suspend without a 30 day, it will be affected immediately.

610
00:49:55,163 --> 00:49:56,764
[SPEAKER_09]: Yes, or near immediately.

611
00:49:58,125 --> 00:50:02,969
[SPEAKER_09]: My possible concern is that I imagine this will happen very often.

612
00:50:03,309 --> 00:50:04,891
[SPEAKER_09]: But if it does happen, there's probably a

613
00:50:06,883 --> 00:50:08,965
[SPEAKER_09]: A reason for that removal or suspension.

614
00:50:09,586 --> 00:50:16,333
[SPEAKER_09]: And so what would it look like for somebody to be removed or suspended and then continue continuing to act on the committee for 30 days?

615
00:50:17,093 --> 00:50:20,316
[SPEAKER_10]: I'm glad you raised that because that is definitely an issue.

616
00:50:21,538 --> 00:50:22,038
[SPEAKER_10]: And I think.

617
00:50:23,459 --> 00:50:26,202
[SPEAKER_10]: I think we can talk about whether.

618
00:50:27,564 --> 00:50:36,848
[SPEAKER_10]: I mean, the subcommittee decided not to give the city council the power to initiate a removal, which is something that the Collins Center talked to us about last meeting.

619
00:50:38,328 --> 00:50:42,310
[SPEAKER_10]: But this does give them some authority in the removal process.

620
00:50:42,430 --> 00:50:44,470
[SPEAKER_10]: So we should talk about whether we want to keep that.

621
00:50:44,871 --> 00:50:45,251
[SPEAKER_10]: Jean?

622
00:50:45,751 --> 00:50:47,532
[SPEAKER_03]: Oh, well, I read it.

623
00:50:47,952 --> 00:50:54,494
[SPEAKER_03]: It says after 30 days, the removal suspension is effective.

624
00:50:55,315 --> 00:50:56,155
[SPEAKER_03]: It's not immediate.

625
00:50:57,142 --> 00:50:57,402
[SPEAKER_10]: Right.

626
00:50:57,762 --> 00:51:04,505
[SPEAKER_10]: And Aubrey's point is that if someone's being removed, they're being removed or suspended for a reason.

627
00:51:05,506 --> 00:51:07,267
[SPEAKER_10]: Oh, I see.

628
00:51:07,367 --> 00:51:08,167
[SPEAKER_10]: Okay, I thought.

629
00:51:09,088 --> 00:51:21,573
[SPEAKER_10]: Then they would have to wait 30, you know, it would give the city council 30 days to disagree with the mayor basically on that.

630
00:51:22,114 --> 00:51:24,435
[SPEAKER_10]: So my feeling is that

631
00:51:27,555 --> 00:51:30,918
[SPEAKER_10]: you know, that we could take that out, but I don't know how other people feel.

632
00:51:32,078 --> 00:51:41,446
[SPEAKER_09]: Another option, just to put it on the table, is for renewables and suspensions to be effective immediately, with a possible reinstatement happening by vote after 30 days.

633
00:51:42,006 --> 00:51:42,366
[SPEAKER_11]: Okay.

634
00:51:42,947 --> 00:51:44,488
[SPEAKER_12]: I think that's a better way of putting it.

635
00:51:44,908 --> 00:51:45,849
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah, I like that.

636
00:51:46,790 --> 00:51:46,970
[SPEAKER_12]: Yeah.

637
00:51:52,292 --> 00:51:56,194
[SPEAKER_10]: So we would say be effective immediately.

638
00:51:56,834 --> 00:51:58,914
[SPEAKER_12]: Effective immediately, yeah.

639
00:51:59,054 --> 00:52:07,277
[SPEAKER_10]: And then the city council would have up to 30 days to reinstate.

640
00:52:07,297 --> 00:52:11,898
[SPEAKER_10]: So I guess,

641
00:52:15,929 --> 00:52:28,457
[SPEAKER_10]: Do we, I mean, this is all standard language and these are powers that other city councils have, but the removal power is less common or the power to have a say over the removal?

642
00:52:31,819 --> 00:52:34,800
[SPEAKER_12]: You know, sometimes a removal is just a removal.

643
00:52:34,901 --> 00:52:38,663
[SPEAKER_12]: There's no option for reinstatement.

644
00:52:40,233 --> 00:52:41,794
[SPEAKER_10]: Right, there would be for this, though.

645
00:52:42,275 --> 00:52:45,698
[SPEAKER_10]: I mean, in this case, the City Council could do it if they wanted to.

646
00:52:45,998 --> 00:52:47,699
[SPEAKER_12]: But why is everything 30 days?

647
00:52:47,940 --> 00:52:49,581
[SPEAKER_12]: Like, why is this 30 days?

648
00:52:49,641 --> 00:52:51,482
[SPEAKER_12]: It's a long period of time for me.

649
00:52:52,463 --> 00:53:01,591
[SPEAKER_10]: Right, because the City Council, because there needs to be time for the City Council to act on things.

650
00:53:03,072 --> 00:53:04,333
[SPEAKER_12]: How often do they meet again?

651
00:53:05,634 --> 00:53:06,215
[SPEAKER_10]: Every other week.

652
00:53:07,120 --> 00:53:10,761
[SPEAKER_12]: Yeah, I mean, you know, I mean, that's a long time for someone to be waiting.

653
00:53:13,501 --> 00:53:18,362
[SPEAKER_10]: Like I said, it's 45 days is actually pretty common in a lot of charters.

654
00:53:19,603 --> 00:53:24,463
[SPEAKER_10]: We could, somebody could suggest lowering it to three weeks, 21 days.

655
00:53:28,444 --> 00:53:30,245
[SPEAKER_02]: Well, this is what we just talked about before.

656
00:53:30,265 --> 00:53:30,945
[SPEAKER_02]: Right.

657
00:53:39,332 --> 00:53:42,694
[SPEAKER_10]: As you pointed out, Paula, this language isn't fine.

658
00:53:46,015 --> 00:53:51,178
[SPEAKER_07]: Why don't we put something in instead of putting a number on it, putting at the,

659
00:53:56,192 --> 00:54:03,036
[SPEAKER_07]: Something, you know, an action to be taken by the city council at their very next meeting.

660
00:54:03,836 --> 00:54:15,523
[SPEAKER_10]: So, um, which, and if there's some reason that they're not meeting right away, or, I mean, I think, I think it would, I think the chart, I think it's pretty standard for the charter to give a time timeframe.

661
00:54:16,203 --> 00:54:16,403
[SPEAKER_07]: Yeah.

662
00:54:18,404 --> 00:54:24,968
[SPEAKER_07]: I mean, the only, the only time where they don't meet generally within two or three weeks,

663
00:54:26,108 --> 00:54:26,851
[SPEAKER_07]: Is the summer.

