675
00:55:44,252 --> 00:55:54,362
[SPEAKER_03]: I don't know if you discuss that as a committee, adding that, or if that would address your concern, Eunice.

676
00:56:00,348 --> 00:56:01,389
[SPEAKER_10]: I mean, that could be added.

677
00:56:03,170 --> 00:56:05,531
[SPEAKER_07]: I mean, define unreasonable.

678
00:56:05,912 --> 00:56:06,812
[SPEAKER_07]: Right, exactly.

679
00:56:06,832 --> 00:56:13,356
[SPEAKER_12]: I mean, yeah.

680
00:56:14,016 --> 00:56:15,717
[SPEAKER_12]: I think we're really overthinking things now.

681
00:56:15,958 --> 00:56:18,179
[SPEAKER_12]: Now that he brought that to my attention, I agree.

682
00:56:18,919 --> 00:56:19,880
[SPEAKER_12]: I think we're overthinking.

683
00:56:21,018 --> 00:56:28,501
[SPEAKER_12]: I think we're trying to be so committed to this and diligent about it.

684
00:56:28,741 --> 00:56:30,562
[SPEAKER_12]: But I do think that there's a little bit.

685
00:56:30,702 --> 00:56:31,122
[SPEAKER_10]: Okay.

686
00:56:31,602 --> 00:56:34,143
[SPEAKER_10]: So Ron, you expressed an intention.

687
00:56:34,243 --> 00:56:42,506
[SPEAKER_10]: But before we do that, I just want to go back to the removal language and we also need to address if we're going to remove the department heads.

688
00:56:42,886 --> 00:56:46,548
[SPEAKER_10]: Because mostly we haven't really been talking about department heads.

689
00:56:46,588 --> 00:56:49,369
[SPEAKER_10]: We're talking about multiple member boards.

690
00:56:50,063 --> 00:56:59,625
[SPEAKER_10]: So, just back to the removal question, are people comfortable with giving the city council the ability to overturn a suspension or a removal?

691
00:57:03,066 --> 00:57:07,487
[SPEAKER_02]: Overturn a suspension, so the mayor makes a suspension.

692
00:57:08,127 --> 00:57:15,269
[SPEAKER_10]: Or removal, which obviously would not happen, it would be probably extraordinary circumstances anyway.

693
00:57:16,469 --> 00:57:18,250
[SPEAKER_02]: Right, but, oh my God, so,

694
00:57:20,618 --> 00:57:28,681
[SPEAKER_02]: So the mayor removes somebody for reasons that may or may not be public.

695
00:57:29,962 --> 00:57:30,202
[SPEAKER_02]: Right.

696
00:57:31,622 --> 00:57:33,463
[SPEAKER_02]: And now we're saying, oh, but that's okay.

697
00:57:34,423 --> 00:57:36,844
[SPEAKER_02]: The city council can overturn it.

698
00:57:38,385 --> 00:57:42,887
[SPEAKER_10]: That's what this would say, unless we decide we don't think that should happen.

699
00:57:43,727 --> 00:57:46,268
[SPEAKER_02]: Well, but there's no talk about

700
00:57:47,020 --> 00:57:52,345
[SPEAKER_02]: What if the person was removed because the person did something inappropriate?

701
00:57:52,966 --> 00:57:55,749
[SPEAKER_02]: Right.

702
00:57:55,949 --> 00:57:56,970
[SPEAKER_02]: As viewed by some.

703
00:57:57,731 --> 00:57:58,011
[SPEAKER_02]: Right.

704
00:57:58,111 --> 00:57:59,393
[SPEAKER_02]: Not necessarily everybody.

705
00:58:01,367 --> 00:58:16,995
[SPEAKER_10]: I mean, and that was what I think that's part of what Aubrey raised, which is why we changed the language to say that it would be effective immediately, but that then the city council would have up to 30 days to overturn them.

706
00:58:19,617 --> 00:58:21,718
[SPEAKER_12]: So that would be these two paragraphs.

707
00:58:22,778 --> 00:58:24,939
[SPEAKER_12]: Could it not be, Milva?

708
00:58:26,360 --> 00:58:29,082
[SPEAKER_12]: I know I read these a couple of days ago and I made some notes on that,

709
00:58:30,675 --> 00:58:34,110
[SPEAKER_12]: If the mayor removes a person for any reason,

710
00:58:35,730 --> 00:58:40,854
[SPEAKER_12]: then why would we grant the city council the authority to reinstate?

711
00:58:41,054 --> 00:58:42,595
[SPEAKER_10]: That is the question we're discussing.

712
00:58:42,696 --> 00:58:47,820
[SPEAKER_10]: And if somebody thinks that that should be removed, they can make a motion and we'll take those two paragraphs out.

713
00:58:48,160 --> 00:58:48,340
[SPEAKER_11]: Right.

714
00:58:48,440 --> 00:58:50,562
[SPEAKER_06]: Well, wouldn't the person have to remove the two paragraphs?

715
00:58:50,582 --> 00:58:52,083
[SPEAKER_12]: Would they have an appeal process?

716
00:58:52,443 --> 00:58:53,924
[SPEAKER_12]: Would there be an appeal process?

717
00:58:54,745 --> 00:59:03,412
[SPEAKER_10]: I think removal then an appeal process, but... I'm pretty sure that the person would have a right to an appeal no matter what.

718
00:59:05,117 --> 00:59:19,949
[SPEAKER_10]: But I mean, that was one of the things that the Collins Center talked about last month with the option of giving the city council the power to initiate a removal was that there could be legal legalities involved.

719
00:59:21,660 --> 00:59:29,943
[SPEAKER_10]: And the fact that even if the city council is approving or rejecting the appointments, the mayor is the appointing authority.

720
00:59:30,063 --> 00:59:41,246
[SPEAKER_10]: So if we gave the city council any power to remove, we would basically be letting someone remove that didn't make the appointment.

721
00:59:42,046 --> 00:59:46,287
[SPEAKER_12]: Yeah, I'm gonna say that I'm not for this.

722
00:59:47,167 --> 00:59:48,288
[SPEAKER_10]: Okay, so I heard a motion.

723
00:59:50,571 --> 00:59:53,613
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah, I make a motion to remove that power out of.

724
00:59:54,094 --> 00:59:55,755
[SPEAKER_08]: I'm going to second that.

725
00:59:56,855 --> 00:59:58,497
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah, yeah.

726
01:00:00,318 --> 01:00:01,959
[SPEAKER_10]: OK, let's do a roll call.

727
01:00:04,000 --> 01:00:12,226
[SPEAKER_10]: So this is a motion to remove the sections that give the City Council authority to overturn mayoral removals or suspensions.

728
01:00:12,626 --> 01:00:14,007
[SPEAKER_10]: Yep.

729
01:00:14,688 --> 01:00:15,589
[SPEAKER_10]: Maury seconded.

730
01:00:15,709 --> 01:00:17,610
[SPEAKER_10]: OK, Eunice.

731
01:00:20,012 --> 01:00:21,153
[SPEAKER_07]: Yeah, go ahead and remove.

732
01:00:21,433 --> 01:00:21,633
[SPEAKER_07]: Yes.

733
01:00:23,054 --> 01:00:23,514
[SPEAKER_10]: Maury.

734
01:00:23,614 --> 01:00:25,215
[SPEAKER_10]: Yes.

735
01:00:25,935 --> 01:00:26,395
[SPEAKER_10]: Paulette.

736
01:00:26,775 --> 01:00:27,036
[SPEAKER_10]: Yes.

737
01:00:28,436 --> 01:00:28,837
[SPEAKER_10]: Phyllis.

738
01:00:29,237 --> 01:00:29,517
[SPEAKER_10]: Yes.

739
01:00:30,497 --> 01:00:30,898
[SPEAKER_10]: Aubrey.

740
01:00:31,678 --> 01:00:31,878
[SPEAKER_09]: Yes.

741
01:00:33,079 --> 01:00:33,459
[SPEAKER_10]: Jean.

742
01:00:39,282 --> 01:00:40,002
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm not sure.

743
01:00:40,022 --> 01:00:49,047
[SPEAKER_03]: If there's a case where things are, people are removed for non

744
01:00:52,362 --> 01:00:55,504
[SPEAKER_03]: That it's political and not because something happened.

745
01:00:57,165 --> 01:00:59,706
[SPEAKER_03]: It happened and has happened in other cities.

746
01:01:00,826 --> 01:01:06,089
[SPEAKER_03]: This gives the city council no opportunity to counter that.

747
01:01:12,252 --> 01:01:12,612
[SPEAKER_03]: I don't know.

748
01:01:12,652 --> 01:01:16,374
[SPEAKER_03]: I guess I'm abstaining because I'm not sure I'm for or against it right now.

749
01:01:16,974 --> 01:01:17,375
[SPEAKER_03]: Okay.

750
01:01:18,115 --> 01:01:19,736
[SPEAKER_03]: But I do have that concern.

751
01:01:21,001 --> 01:01:24,243
[SPEAKER_10]: Okay, my box is moved, so I don't know, Ron?

752
01:01:25,623 --> 01:01:26,024
[SPEAKER_04]: Did I get?

753
01:01:27,725 --> 01:01:31,166
[SPEAKER_10]: You said no, you vote not to remove it?

754
01:01:31,526 --> 01:01:31,787
[SPEAKER_04]: Correct.

755
01:01:31,867 --> 01:01:32,167
[SPEAKER_10]: Okay.

756
01:01:37,049 --> 01:01:38,670
[SPEAKER_10]: I missed one person, who did I miss?

757
01:01:39,110 --> 01:01:39,611
[SPEAKER_11]: Yourself?

758
01:01:39,731 --> 01:01:40,011
[SPEAKER_11]: Me.

759
01:01:41,051 --> 01:01:42,472
[SPEAKER_10]: Anthony.

760
01:01:42,852 --> 01:01:43,233
[SPEAKER_10]: Anthony.

761
01:01:44,293 --> 01:01:44,513
[SPEAKER_06]: Yes.

762
01:01:44,833 --> 01:01:45,454
[SPEAKER_06]: And you vote yes.

