01:31:53,093 --> 01:31:59,735
[SPEAKER_02]: The thing that, so I'm a little uncertain about where to go with some things with the subcommittee because we didn't get a great response.

1201
01:32:02,696 --> 01:32:06,298
[SPEAKER_02]: We had talked about having another session with school committee members.

1202
01:32:06,358 --> 01:32:10,799
[SPEAKER_02]: I just didn't see, right now the new ones are all focused on being new ones.

1203
01:32:11,620 --> 01:32:16,862
[SPEAKER_02]: And I did get a couple of emails and I'll share them with the subcommittee from a few,

1204
01:32:17,943 --> 01:32:27,197
[SPEAKER_02]: Members, but just a few but part of the problem is one person says this and the next person says this the next person says this and you know there's not a.

1205
01:32:29,277 --> 01:32:30,919
[SPEAKER_02]: I don't see any consensus building.

1206
01:32:30,979 --> 01:32:33,621
[SPEAKER_02]: That's the thing that's concerning me.

1207
01:32:33,661 --> 01:32:35,963
[SPEAKER_02]: And there's not enough to really to feel that yet.

1208
01:32:36,524 --> 01:32:45,052
[SPEAKER_02]: I will tell you that Melvin and I did go to speak to the superintendent of schools, Dr. Maurice Edward Vincent.

1209
01:32:45,512 --> 01:32:49,255
[SPEAKER_02]: I think we had a wonderful discussion that went for more than an hour.

1210
01:32:50,256 --> 01:32:55,558
[SPEAKER_02]: And there was something that was just so clear and dominant in her discussion.

1211
01:32:55,718 --> 01:32:57,818
[SPEAKER_02]: And as a member, I totally get it.

1212
01:32:58,578 --> 01:33:06,941
[SPEAKER_02]: And that is, she said, how difficult it is for her as the leader of the school system to have to, every two years,

1213
01:33:07,781 --> 01:33:12,222
[SPEAKER_02]: have a new, potentially new set of school committee members.

1214
01:33:12,702 --> 01:33:20,665
[SPEAKER_02]: And she says that, she said that, you know, you come to an agreement with one set, you've hashed it out, maybe it's taken you a year to get there.

1215
01:33:21,365 --> 01:33:23,846
[SPEAKER_02]: And then all of a sudden, they're leaving again.

1216
01:33:24,006 --> 01:33:30,868
[SPEAKER_02]: And I do know as a member of the school committee, one of the things that we always sort of felt like, okay, the first year after you got elected,

1217
01:33:31,588 --> 01:33:32,469
[SPEAKER_02]: You got stuff done.

1218
01:33:33,150 --> 01:33:35,392
[SPEAKER_02]: And then the second year, everybody was running.

1219
01:33:36,073 --> 01:33:43,381
[SPEAKER_02]: And you could you could tell on the floor when people started campaigning, you know, it just you couldn't help.

1220
01:33:43,401 --> 01:33:45,403
[SPEAKER_02]: You know, it's just sort of like it was so clear.

1221
01:33:46,023 --> 01:33:47,805
[SPEAKER_02]: So she said if there was only one.

1222
01:33:48,806 --> 01:34:05,672
[SPEAKER_02]: thing that she could say to our committee is if we could change the two-year terms to four-year terms, that she thought it would be such a more efficient and effective way for her as the leader of the school department to accomplish anything.

1223
01:34:06,313 --> 01:34:12,655
[SPEAKER_02]: So as we talk about the city council, I mean, so that's a really, it was a very strong viewpoint, right, Melva?

1224
01:34:13,215 --> 01:34:17,477
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah, that was, she was pretty flexible on everything, but that was her one thing that she

1225
01:34:19,182 --> 01:34:20,464
[SPEAKER_10]: express a strong opinion on.

1226
01:34:20,484 --> 01:34:21,004
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah.

1227
01:34:21,585 --> 01:34:25,409
[SPEAKER_02]: And, and, and, and substantiated very articulately, I think.

1228
01:34:26,090 --> 01:34:31,796
[SPEAKER_02]: So, so part of that then is, and that's why I said, well, you know, we're now we're talking about city council.

1229
01:34:31,876 --> 01:34:34,018
[SPEAKER_02]: And when you think about it, it's the same problem.

1230
01:34:34,519 --> 01:34:36,881
[SPEAKER_02]: And it's really the same problem for the mayor is that

1231
01:34:37,742 --> 01:34:41,544
[SPEAKER_02]: Um, you know, when you've got two years, I can tell you two years.

1232
01:34:41,624 --> 01:34:54,290
[SPEAKER_02]: I mean, I would obviously love three, but three years gets you into this problem of holding the election unless you change the election cycle altogether and put it in the spring the way many communities have it.

1233
01:34:54,891 --> 01:35:01,494
[SPEAKER_02]: But I'm not sure in Medford where we are very used to having the November election cycle.

1234
01:35:01,954 --> 01:35:08,341
[SPEAKER_02]: Three years, you know, would really get you a better, I think, plan.

1235
01:35:08,862 --> 01:35:12,366
[SPEAKER_02]: But then who would come and vote in the spring?

1236
01:35:12,586 --> 01:35:16,971
[SPEAKER_02]: You know, you can't do it on, you can't have elections

1237
01:35:19,980 --> 01:35:28,426
[SPEAKER_02]: every, you know, if we changed it to every four years, it is a longer time and it certainly would be a change for us.

1238
01:35:30,047 --> 01:35:32,388
[SPEAKER_02]: But I think it's really worth thinking about.

1239
01:35:33,629 --> 01:35:44,616
[SPEAKER_02]: So that again was, again, it's her, it's one person's thought, but I think that it was a very valuable discussion to have with her.

1240
01:35:45,136 --> 01:35:46,898
[SPEAKER_10]: So when we address term lengths,

1241
01:35:49,646 --> 01:35:56,393
[SPEAKER_10]: You know, we can, I mean, we can address term lengths for all the different branches of government.

1242
01:35:56,433 --> 01:36:07,044
[SPEAKER_10]: And I think that makes sense because it will affect, they're interrelated because of the way elections run.

1243
01:36:07,724 --> 01:36:09,907
[SPEAKER_10]: So we'll definitely look at that soon.

1244
01:36:11,290 --> 01:36:13,951
[SPEAKER_02]: So other than that, I don't have much to say.

1245
